    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="850"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d850">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 882.51/313C.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Special Representative of Dr. Falkner</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 27, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to yesterday’s cable,<note n="1" xml:id="d850fn1">Not printed.</note>
                    Liberian Government is probably about to default on interest on 1871 loan due
                    April 1. If this should occur it will change the situation as regards
                    negotiations with bondholders. Have cabled Monrovia for explanation; until this
                    is received you will await in London further instructions from Department. In
                    Department’s opinion this situation means merely slight delay and need not
                    interfere with the plans of General Receiver Clark.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
